1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. Nf3 e6 5. Be2 Nd7 6. O-O Ne7 7. Nbd2 Bg6 8. Nh4
c5 9. Nxg6 hxg6 10. c3 Nc6 11. Nf3 Be7 12. Be3 {I had checked this position
superficially before the game and figured I would have an improved French
Defence. Without the bishop on c8 and having such a compact pawn structure
things couldn't be better for Black! On closer inspection I became less happy
with the line I chose, Black's king has no save haven; short castling always
runs into the plan g3-h4-Kg2-Rh1-h5 with an attack, while long castling is not
desirable because Black wants to push his pawns on that wing. Furthermore
White has the simple plan of pushing g3-h4 which usually results in an
annoying initiative on the kingside. I would recommend players defending the
Black side of the Caro-Kann to check 5...c5 which seems to be the correct way.
Back to the game, I decided not to decide the positioning of my king just yet
but first grabbed some space on the queenside.} a6 13. g3 b5 (13... g5 $5 {was
tried previously but this solution of meeting h4 seems a bit to radical to me.}
) 14. h4 Nb6 15. b3 (15. dxc5 Na4 {would not be an improvement over the game
for White. I am however not sure if the text move is the strongest; of course
it takes away the square c4 from the knight but it also creates a point of
attack for Black.}) 15... c4 16. Kg2 ({The position is very interesting from a
strategic point of view. First of all, many engines will tell you, White is
better after} 16. a4 $6 {but it is exactly the opposite:} Na5 17. axb5 axb5 18.
b4 Nb3 19. Rxa8 Qxa8 {with a nice initiative for Black.}) ({The same goes for} 
16. b4 $6 a5 17. a3 Ra7 18. Kg2 Qa8 {with nice play for Black. White's best is
therefore to stick to his initial plans of grabbing the initiative on the
other wing. The move 16.Kg2 serves that plan very well, making way for the
rook to go to h1.}) 16... a5 {Now White has to reckon with ideas involving
pushing a4, forcing b4, than continuing a3-Na4 followed by a sacrifice on c3
or b4. The two pawns could prove more valuable then a piece. Another idea is
to push ...b4, opening the position on the queenside.} 17. Nd2 Rc8 ({Now} 17...
b4 {doesn't work} 18. bxc4 dxc4 (18... bxc3 19. c5 cxd2 20. cxb6 {White is
much better}) 19. cxb4 axb4 20. Nxc4 $1 Qd5+ $140 21. Bf3 Qxc4 22. Rc1 {
winning material.}) ({and the sacrificial ideas after} 17... a4 18. b4 a3 {are
parried by} 19. Qc1 $1 {for example} Nxb4 (19... Na4 20. Qxa3 {and Black can't
profit from the stange position of White's queen.}) 20. cxb4 Bxb4 21. Rb1 {
Black's compensation is not enough. With the textmove I am trying to make the
b4-push possible.}) 18. Rc1 {Prophylactic measures against ...b4.} a4 $5 19.
bxc4 ({Since} 19. b4 a3 $1 {followed b4 Na4 gives White no chances of
preventing the strong sacrifices on c3 or b4.}) 19... bxc4 $6 ({A strategic 
error, which gets me into real trouble. I had visions of playing a3-Na4 and
Rb8-b2 but this is way too optimistic. Instead I should go for} 19... dxc4 20.
Rh1 (20. Ne4 b4 {gives good counterplay.}) 20... Nd5 21. Ne4 {but, I must
admit, White is better here as well.}) 20. Qc2 a3 {Creating an outpost on b2.}
21. Rb1 Ra8 {Facilitating a route for the knight to reach b2.} 22. Bg4 $1 {
Around here I started to realise things really weren't going that great. White
prepares Nf3-Bg5 and makes sure that I will have to watch out for Bxe6 all the
time.} Na4 23. Nf3 Qd7 ({I didn't like the look of} 23... Qa5 24. Bxe6 $1 Qxc3
(24... fxe6 25. Qxg6+) 25. Bxd5 Qxc2 26. Bxc6+ Kd8 27. Bxa8 {with d4-d5-d6 to
come.}) 24. Rh1 {White is conducting the game very well, now h5 is on the
cards while my queenside play is -let's put it mildly- disappointing.} Kd8 $5 {
The start of a heroic journey by his majesty.} 25. h5 gxh5 26. Bxh5 Rf8 (26...
g6 {fails to} 27. Bxg6 Rxh1 28. Rxh1 fxg6 29. Rh8+) 27. Bg4 Kc7 28. Rh7 Rg8 29.
Bh5 {Forcing me to further weaken my queenside.} g6 30. Bg4 Qe8 31. Rbh1 $6 ({
This looks a bit slow, I think} 31. Bg5 Rh8 32. Rxh8 Qxh8 33. Bxe7 Nxe7 34. Ng5
{deserves serious attention.}) 31... Kb6 {I like this move, taking advantage
of the fact that White's rook just left the b-file. On the 7th rank my king is
more vulnerable to Bxe6-ideas while on a5 (yes, that's where he is going!) he
is supporting counterplay by Rb8-b2. It is suprisingly difficult for White to
break through here, and we were of course running out of time as well.} 32. Ng5
{A difficult decision. As I mentioned before White was perhaps better off
exchanging bishops on g5, keeping the knight to pressure f7.} Bxg5 33. Bxg5 Ka5
34. Rb1 Rh8 {It is important to exchange this strong rook.} 35. Rxh8 Qxh8 36.
Rb7 (36. Bc1 Qf8 37. Rb7 Ra7 38. Qb1 (38. Rxa7+ Nxa7 39. Bd1 Nb6 {is OK for
Black as well, the knights are a good match for the bishops.}) 38... Nb2 $1 {
holds, because of} 39. Rxa7+ Nxa7 40. Bxb2 Qb8 $1) 36... Qf8 {Preparing Ra7
when my position is saved.} 37. Qc1 $5 Ka6 $1 ({White's last move is not easy
to meet with little time on the clock. His idea is} 37... Rb8 38. Bh6 $1 Qe8
39. Rxb8 Qxb8 40. Qxa3 {with a win.}) 38. Rc7 Kb6 39. Rd7 Qe8 40. Rd6 {This is
the position I spent my last minutes on, White's rook looks strong but is also
close to being trapped.} Nb2 (40... Kc7 $5 41. Qxa3 Nb6 42. Qc5 Na4 43. Qa3 Nb6
{would have been a draw.}) 41. Bd1 $2 ({Accompanied by a draw offer. It is
very difficult when you have been pressing the whole game and finding yourself
having to switch to defence. Black is threatening  Kc7-Na5-Nb7, winning the
rook. White has to act directly in order to stop it.} 41. Qf4 $1 {now} Kc7 42.
Qf6 {is dangerous for Black because Bxe6 is coming. Black should chose 41...
Na4 forcing the queen's retreat 42.Qc1 when 42...Nb2 draws.}) 41... Kc7 42. Bc2
Na5 $1 43. Bf4 Nb7 44. g4 Nxd6 45. exd6+ Kc6 46. Bg3 Qd8 47. Qh6 Na4 48. Qe3
Nb6 49. Bd1 Nc8 50. Bf3 Nxd6 {And the rest is easy.} 51. Qc1 g5 52. Qb1 Qa5 53.
Bxd6 Kxd6 54. Qb7 Qa7 55. Qb4+ Kd7 56. Bd1 Qa5 57. Qb7+ Ke8 58. Qc6+ Ke7 59.
Qb7+ Kf8 60. Bc2 Kg7 61. Bb1 Qd8 0-1

